          "body": "Verses 16-18 perform a final survey of the devastation before Joel turns to prayer. Food is cut off before their eyes (1:16) — the eyewitness force is deliberate; this is not theoretical suffering but visible, daily deprivation. Joy and gladness have departed from the house of God (1:16) — the temple liturgy was not only oblation but celebration (Psalm 122:1-4); both are silenced. Seeds shrivel under their clods (1:17) — the farming season has failed at its very beginning, in the soil, before harvest was ever possible. The storehouses are desolate, the barns torn down (1:17). And the animals groan (1:18) — the herds wander aimlessly for lack of pasture; even the sheep suffer. Joel's catalog is pastoral and specific, not abstractly theological. He wants the community to feel the full weight of what has been lost before he tells them to whom to bring it."
