          "body": "The chapter does not end with more description. It ends with the prophet himself modeling the only adequate response: 'To You, O LORD, I cry' (1:19). This is not theological information delivered from a safe professional distance — it is the prophet entering his own summons. Joel 1 has called the drunkards to weep (1:5), the farmers to wail (1:11), the priests to lament (1:13), and the congregation to cry out (1:14). Now Joel himself cries. The prayer is brief and honest: fire has devoured the pastures; the water brooks are dried up. Even the beasts pant for the Lord (1:20). The chapter's final image is the entirety of the created order — prophet, priest, farmer, and animal — straining toward God as the only source of life in a land that has gone dry. This is the canonical shape of biblical lament: describe the loss fully, name it honestly, and turn it into address. The horizon of Joel 2 — where God promises to restore the years the locust has eaten (2:25) — is only reachable through the honest grief of Joel 1."
